    <a name="4943"></a>
    <img src="/images/photos/CEA-logo.gif">
    <div class="article-content">
        <div class="sub-content-header">Senator Tom Coburn M.D., Representative Anna Eshoo and Dr. Robert Kahn to be Honored at CEA's Digital Patriots Dinner</div>
        <span class="smallText">Apr 05, 2011 11:27:30</span>
        
        
        <p>Sen. Tom A. Coburn, M.D. (R-OK) and Rep. Anna G. Eshoo (D-CA) will be recognized for their unwavering support of technology innovation during the seventh annual Digital Patriots Dinner on May 11. They will join Dr. Robert E. Kahn, chairman, CEO and president of the Corporation for National Research Initiatives (CNRI), in receiving their awards at the Andrew W. Mellon Auditorium in Washington, D.C. <br />
        <br />
        “The Digital Patriots Dinner honors policy leaders and industry visionaries who are passionate about technology. They know that our industry creates jobs, improves our lives and drives the American economy” said Gary Shapiro, president and CEO, CEA. “We are excited to recognize the 2011 Digital Patriots for their contributions to advancing innovation. By helping to create the internet, Dr. Kahn enabled our digital age. Through their work in Congress, Senator Coburn and Representative Eshoo ensure our public policies allow us to be the world’s innovation leader.” <br />
        <br />
        Tom A. Coburn, M.D. was elected to the U.S. Senate on November 2, 2004. Dr. Coburn's priorities in the Senate include reducing spending, protecting liberties, balancing the budget and improving health care access and affordability. He is a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee, and the Committee on Finance. In 2006, Dr. Coburn teamed up with then-Senator Barack Obama to create USAspending.gov, an online database of all federal spending. Prior to his election to the Senate, Dr. Coburn represented Oklahoma's Second Congressional District in the House of Representatives from 1995 through 2001. <br />
        <br />
        Anna G. Eshoo was first sworn in as a member of the U.S. House of Representatives in 1993. For nearly two decades in Congress she has defended consumers, promoted American competitiveness and innovation, fought for access to health care, protected the environment and encouraged development of clean energy technology. Rep. Eshoo has served on the House Energy and Commerce Committee since 1995 and is Ranking Member of the Subcommittee on Communications and Technology, which has primary jurisdiction over the Internet and telecommunications. Rep. Eshoo also co-chairs the Congressional Internet Caucus, the NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus and the House Medical Technology Caucus, and serves as Vice Chair of the 21st Century Health Care Caucus. <br />
        <br />
        Robert E. Kahn founded CNRI in 1986 as a not-for-profit organization to provide leadership and funding for research and development for the National Information Infrastructure. In 1972, Dr. Kahn moved to the U.S. Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) and subsequently became Director of DARPA's Information Processing Techniques Office (IPTO). Dr. Kahn conceived the idea of open-architecture networking and is a co-inventor of the TCP/IP protocols. Dr. Kahn also coined the term National Information Infrastructure (NII), which later became more widely known as the Information Super Highway. In December 1997, President Clinton presented the U.S. National Medal of Technology to Dr. Kahn and Vinton G. Cerf for founding and developing the Internet. They both received various other awards including the ACM Turing Award and the Presidential Medal of Freedom from President George W. Bush in 2005. <br />
        <br />
        All proceeds from the Digital Patriots Dinner ticket sales and sponsorships will be donated directly to the D.C. Opportunity Scholarship Program by CEA. The D.C. Opportunity Scholarship Program (also known as the D.C. School Choice Incentive Program) was created in 2004 to provide low-income parents residing in the District of Columbia with expanded options for the education of their children. It is the first federally-funded K-12 scholarship program in the nation’s history. <br />
        <br />
        The Digital Patriots Dinner will be held in conjunction with CES on the Hill, scheduled May 10 at the Eastern Market in D.C., which will showcase cutting-edge innovations and demonstrate policy issues affecting the consumer technology industry. For more information or to register for the Digital Patriots Dinner and CES on the Hill, visit <a  target="_blank" href="http://CE.org/events">CE.org/events</a>. </p>
    
    
